Upon entering the first thing that hit was the smell of chlorine - and the familiarity was nice. While back on Earth Houston had started almost every morning at 0600 hours exactly within the swimming facilities of the school he taught at, spending up to two hours there before dragging himself off to get ready before classes. It used to be part of his daily routine but he had fallen out of practice when he joined Starfleet; he had thought that his workload at the school was intense? It had been nothing compared to becoming a Starfleet counsellor, genuinely. Things were non-stop here. Inhaling deeply and smiling slightly at the smell of chlorine and the warmth of the area, he wandered through to the changing area... And emerged a short while later in black jammer-style swimshorts and a short-sleeved rash guard. It didn't do perfectly to conceal exactly how thin he was but it helped somewhat - the trace of his ribs was prominent but nowhere as near as bad as it would have been had he showed up shirtless. He stuck his head under the showers to the side for a moment and ran his hands through his hair to break down the mass amount of hairspray which held it up before he slowly made his way to the side of the pool. Selecting one of the lanes which had been cordoned off for swimming lengths - the one closest to the edge, thankfully, because he knew he didn't have the stamina that he used to and he may have to stop - he sat down at the edge and put his feet and lower legs into the water. Not a bad temperature, really... With that he slid off to stand in it and took a moment to briefly sink his head under the surface and let his antennae adjust to the pressure of the water. They always were such an issue when swimming; they caused a bit of an issue when it came to being aerodynamic.
Figuring he should just start as he always used to, Houston grasped the edge with his right hand and placed both feet upon the side, shifting so he was just balanced with his toes touching the wall. He stretched out with his left arm ready, inhaled in preparation… And then with a glance up at the large clock at the end pushed himself off from the wall, bringing both hands together and cutting through the water with ease. Within a few seconds he had settled into a steady front crawl, falling back into the pattern with ease and even managing to remember how to do the flip-turn at the end. Swimming really was one of those things that you never forgot how to do, huh? It was nice…

Captain Syrezeaju 25-Apr-20 10:07 PM
The familiar smell of chlorine hit almost immediately upon entering. It was pleasant, strangely soothing; almost immediately the tension began to unknot from his shoulders. Falling back into familiarity amidst a life of pure confusion was nice. He padded through to the changing area and emerged a few minutes later, now clad in black jammer-style swimshorts and a long-sleeved rash guard. Interstellar Olympics had gotten very good at adapting sports clothing to accommodate necessary temperature changes in different species. This fabric was made to filter water which was far too hot for an andorian and make it cool instead. Pausing at the small room to the side he ducked his head under the shower and ruffled his hair to break down the hairspray which kept it upright, and then headed through to the pool. A couple of lanes had been cordoned off for swimming lengths. Sitting at the edge he slid into the water, grimacing for a moment at the temperature until he could get used to it. In a deft movement he then quickly sunk his head underwater, antennae and all, to get used to the pressure. Goggles which had been placed atop his head, just short of his his antennae, were then tugged down. Left hand grasped the indented edge of the pool, right stretched out, legs drawn in and toes touching the wall. He counted down from five, inhaled deeply, sunk his face into the water... And then pushed off from the edge, bringing both hands together. There was that brief moment of gliding - cutting through the water - before he settled into a steady freestyle crawl. One, two, three strokes; exhale as you do. Turn your head, inhale. One, two, three. So on, and so on. Tuck at the end, push off; flip-turn done. No need to break any world records, here.
